Now, I didn't realize
this is the BBC.

00:39:04.830 --> 00:39:09.090
So, the producer came
back with 10,000 stories.

00:39:09.090 --> 00:39:15.440
I said look, I could do--
I'll do four of them.

00:39:16.650 --> 00:39:19.380
And I was flooded with stories.

00:39:19.380 --> 00:39:23.660
I was just-- it was just--
it was terrific to have them.

00:39:23.660 --> 00:39:30.270
But-- And what I found was that
the new stories were trying

00:39:30.270 --> 00:39:35.360
to be outside the 10 classes
that I've already decided

00:39:35.360 --> 00:39:38.180
where the extremes of
all classes of stories.

00:39:38.180 --> 00:39:43.300
And, you know, I think there
are maybe 11 or 12 classes now

00:39:43.300 --> 00:39:45.800
of which I didn't think of.

00:39:45.800 --> 00:39:51.280
I mean, I just got one
yesterday or the day before.

00:39:51.280 --> 00:39:55.720
A guy lost a wallet on the
Staten Island Ferry just

00:39:55.720 --> 00:39:57.020
over the overboard.

00:39:57.020 --> 00:39:59.420
I don't know how you lose a
wallet overboard in Staten.

00:39:59.420 --> 00:40:08.250
And he said a fisherman friend
of his six months later in--

00:40:08.250 --> 00:40:11.230
on Cape Cod found his wallet.

00:40:11.230 --> 00:40:16.230
Now, that is a category
all by itself.

00:40:18.360 --> 00:40:20.760
But, you know, once you get
all these stories you have

00:40:20.760 --> 00:40:23.510
to be very careful about putting
it into a non-fiction book.

00:40:23.510 --> 00:40:25.450
So I have to vet those stories.

00:40:25.450 --> 00:40:28.370
They really-- I mean, I
didn't know this person.

00:40:28.370 --> 00:40:30.110
How do I make sure that's true?

00:40:30.110 --> 00:40:31.570
It's such a wonderful story.

00:40:31.570 --> 00:40:35.900
It's such almost impossible
story but yet, you know,

00:40:35.900 --> 00:40:38.300
you have to vet these because
this is non-fiction book.

00:40:38.300 --> 00:40:41.520
So, it's a-- there
are other categories

00:40:41.520 --> 00:40:44.190
that I had not even thought about.

00:40:44.190 --> 00:40:45.490
&gt;&gt; Joel Achenbach: Before
we go to the next question,

00:40:45.490 --> 00:40:48.940
a question that's been rattling
around my head for a while is,

00:40:48.940 --> 00:40:52.390
so we're coming to this
age of self-driving cars

00:40:52.390 --> 00:40:56.000
which statistically we are
told will be much safer.

00:40:56.000 --> 00:40:58.480
But I'd like to have my
hands on the wheel, you know.

00:40:58.480 --> 00:40:59.930
I mean I like to be driving myself.

00:40:59.930 --> 00:41:03.810
So, although I know
rationally that it's better

00:41:03.810 --> 00:41:07.330
if the car drives itself, you know,

00:41:07.330 --> 00:41:09.530
do I trust those algorithms
in there?

00:41:09.530 --> 00:41:12.400
And I mean, you know,
isn't it human nature not

00:41:12.400 --> 00:41:17.850
to really trust the math entirely
because it's different for me?

00:41:17.850 --> 00:41:20.040
You know what I'm saying?

00:41:20.040 --> 00:41:21.680
Does that make sense?

00:41:21.680 --> 00:41:22.980
&gt;&gt; Joseph Mazur: Yeah,
but let's say this.

00:41:22.980 --> 00:41:30.030
If you were being-- to be asked to
be an astronaut to go to the moon,

00:41:30.030 --> 00:41:35.350
would you trust the thrusters
of that rocket ship that's going

00:41:35.350 --> 00:41:37.040
to bring you to the moon?

00:41:37.040 --> 00:41:39.890
&gt;&gt; Joel Achenbach: I'd
question the management at NASA.

00:41:41.230 --> 00:41:43.870
&gt;&gt; Joseph Mazur: Yeah, you might
but you'd have to have that trust.

00:41:43.870 --> 00:41:45.170
&gt;&gt; Joel Achenbach: Yeah.

00:41:45.170 --> 00:41:46.470
&gt;&gt; Joseph Mazur: Because
you're not driving that thing.

00:41:46.470 --> 00:41:47.770
&gt;&gt; Joel Achenbach: No, that's true.

00:41:47.770 --> 00:41:49.070
&gt;&gt; Joseph Mazur: Yeah.

00:41:49.070 --> 00:41:50.370
&gt;&gt; Joel Achenbach:
But that-- would you--

00:41:50.370 --> 00:41:51.670
now you're being rational again.

00:41:51.670 --> 00:41:52.970
All right, let's go ahead, OK.

00:41:52.970 --> 00:41:56.230
&gt;&gt; I don't mean to make this
the religious question line

00:41:56.230 --> 00:41:59.970
but when you're talking
about probability,

00:41:59.970 --> 00:42:04.380
chance and as you brought
up here, we're here,

00:42:04.380 --> 00:42:07.780
you have all these
probabilities, how is it possible.

00:42:07.780 --> 00:42:12.580
You said you had gotten to points
where you thought about God

00:42:12.580 --> 00:42:16.990
or spiritual influence and I was
curious about how far you went

00:42:16.990 --> 00:42:20.450
with that considering the last
maybe 150 years there's a drought

00:42:20.450 --> 00:42:23.310
of religion and science?

00:42:23.310 --> 00:42:24.800
So, yeah, that was my question.

00:42:24.800 --> 00:42:26.100
&gt;&gt; Joseph Mazur: Yeah.

00:42:26.100 --> 00:42:28.780
It's something I have
thought about and I confess

00:42:28.780 --> 00:42:33.010
that there are things
that we just don't know.

00:42:33.010 --> 00:42:35.210
I mean, there are a lot of
things that we do not know.

00:42:35.210 --> 00:42:39.340
I mean, if you think of
what the future has for us,

00:42:39.340 --> 00:42:41.200
it's very hard to predict
the future.

00:42:41.200 --> 00:42:43.680
I mean, 50 years ago,
would we have thought

00:42:43.680 --> 00:42:46.530
that we could just all have
cellphones anywhere we go?

00:42:46.530 --> 00:42:51.090
I mean, that's, you know, that
kind of thing is just so foreign

00:42:51.090 --> 00:42:56.990
and we just wouldn't know that
there is actually some kind of a,

00:42:56.990 --> 00:43:01.010
you know, an action at a
distance that gives everybody

00:43:01.010 --> 00:43:02.990
in this room a telephone number

00:43:02.990 --> 00:43:05.470
and they can all have
cellphones in their pockets.

00:43:05.470 --> 00:43:07.840
I mean that's something
that's so extraordinary.

00:43:07.840 --> 00:43:09.140
Why is it extraordinary?

00:43:09.140 --> 00:43:12.670
Well, because I don't see any
attachments to these things.

00:43:12.670 --> 00:43:16.000 position:56%
I mean, I don't see the connections.

00:43:16.000 --> 00:43:19.970
But how do we know that our
heads aren't really doing

00:43:19.970 --> 00:43:21.630
something together?

00:43:21.630 --> 00:43:26.950
It's possible and I wouldn't,
you know, I'm not saying this is,

00:43:26.950 --> 00:43:30.340
you know, with any
conviction here but I am saying

00:43:30.340 --> 00:43:34.440 position:56%
that we do have electromagnet fields
go running around in our heads

00:43:34.440 --> 00:43:35.740
or just the top of my head.

00:43:35.740 --> 00:43:37.510
I mean, I can't feel it but I think

00:43:37.510 --> 00:43:40.370
that there is an electromagnetic
field.

00:43:40.370 --> 00:43:43.890
I mean, we are chemical
electric in circuitry.

00:43:43.890 --> 00:43:45.190
&gt;&gt; Joel Achenbach: I can feel it.

00:43:45.190 --> 00:43:46.490
&gt;&gt; Joseph Mazur: You can feel?

00:43:46.490 --> 00:43:47.790
&gt;&gt; Joel Achenbach: I can feel it.

00:43:47.790 --> 00:43:49.090
&gt;&gt; Joseph Mazur: Well,
but he has hair.

00:43:49.090 --> 00:43:52.190
&gt;&gt; Joel Achenbach: But this close
to him, I mean it's as radiant.

00:43:52.190 --> 00:43:54.050
I think we'll have to
wrap this up in a second.

00:43:54.050 --> 00:43:55.350
&gt;&gt; Joseph Mazur: Yup.

00:43:55.350 --> 00:43:56.650
&gt;&gt; Joel Achenbach: You know,

00:43:56.650 --> 00:43:57.950
you already did your
book signing, right?

00:43:57.950 --> 00:43:59.250
&gt;&gt; Joseph Mazur: I'm going
to do a book signing, yes.

00:43:59.250 --> 00:44:00.550
&gt;&gt; Joel Achenbach: What
